posts.body:
>>934dd4f1-187a-416f-8edb-0f77b411fa72

Something is really wrong with your setup. While there is a new phenomenon I've noticed where occasionally posts "hang" while trying to contact the last 3 peers....Other times, those posts just fly. As fast or faster than client server boards.

And downloads from many boards are very quick now.

Maybe twofish can troubleshoot?

Currently showing 53 connections on the main page. 16 connected and 101 onions on pol.

Is it possible everyone migrated to onions and you are the only party remaining on clearnet? Is this Windows or Linux?

Piss off your ISP?   :)

>>12d4ec89-11f1-4359-9380-c8016fd705fc
Posting 12197 just flew. Probably just a better circuit Tor selected. Changes every 10 minutes.

Also possible you have a shitty guard relay. Tor needs to do a better job clearing those out or find some way users can blacklist bad guards. Doesn't not come up often...but when it does - maddening.

>>a137ec4a-c6f6-4d40-b291-c2e40cd23731
Not knowledgeable enough to comment on ZeroNet's design or scaling capacity. Just noting that it is one of the few free platforms we have.

With Youtube, Twitter,  Facebook becoming increasingly restrictive and selective, it is essential that ALL of us arrive upon a truly bulletproof setup. It's gotta work.

Why I encourage you to document everything you can - then get it back to the mad Hungarian. He needs to know about these difficulties.

Sending some money would be a good thing too if you can manage it. I'm certain this project of his is cannibalizing his own personal budget.

Don't send money to the Tor organization. They are getting woke. Instead figure out what you must do to construct and maintain a Tor relay. Wade through the hassles and just do it.

>>934dd4f1-187a-416f-8edb-0f77b411fa72
BTW, have a healthy I2P relay now which moves a lot of traffic. Everything works. I2P still sucks pretty bad (IMO).

Still plan to keep it running as a fallback. Will just cuss about it.

Wish someone would demonstrate how I can build a quality low power ZeroNet box so I can keep it running 24/7 :( We don't have a lot of experts to pull from.

posts.subject: My own ZeroNet system works very well with only occasional glitches. Very fast now.
posts.body:
But boy other people are having problems :( And if this shit doesn't get fixed - we'll lose those potential users. Which would be a tragedy.....

A millionaire or billionaire could really leave his mark if he brought discipline to these free networks. Slapping Poindexters until they made it work right.

Freenets must OUTPERFORM captivenets if they are ever to replace them.

>>e24da6f1-ed9f-4f56-93e0-c7cf683e0e41
It is an unusual format in that he used a variable bit rate...probably a way to reduce filesize and maintain quality. He knew what he was doing in that it plays in two browsers here. Both Firefox and Tor browser play it without issue (surprising).

I'm no fan of Google, but their public webm standard has much to commend it. Had he stored it in that format you would have most certainly been able to use it - but at reduced video quality.

It's annoying that we still have issues with video in 2020. When does it end?

I prefer straight X264 with AAC or AC3 inside mkv containers. Unfortunately browser coders have never supported that format natively, nor does the Zeronet server. It's a goddamn shame.

Made worse because webm is a pain in the ass to work with. Few tools available.
